Vente Cloning and Heterologous Expression of the Aranciamycin Biosynthetic Gene Cluster Revealed a New Flexible Glycosyltransferase Andriy Luzhetskyy,[a] Almuth Mayer,[a] Jens Hoffmann,[c] Stefan Pelzer,[b] Meike Holzenk(cid:30)mper,[b] Bettina Schmitt,[b] Sven-Eric Wohlert,[b] Andreas Vente,[b] and Andreas Bechthold*[a]

Many anthracycline drugs are composed of a tetracyclic aro- matic polyketide planar scaffold coupled with l-deoxysugars. The main molecular target that determines the clinical activity of these compounds is the poisoning of DNA topoisomer- Gase II.[1, 2] The four major anthracyclines in clinical use are dox- orubicin, daunorubicin, epirubicin and idarubicin. These com- pounds are approved for the treatment of breast and small cell lung cancers, acute myeloid leukemia, pancreatic and gas- tric cancers, different sarcomas, and others.[3, 4] The clinical ap- plication of anthracyclines is limited by their dose-related side effects, which include bone marrow toxicity, gastrointestinal disorders, stomatitis, alopecia, acute and cumulative cardiotox- icity as well as extravasation.[5] The antitumor potency and toxi- cological profile of the anthracyclines have been powerful stimuli for an industrial search for more effective and less toxic anthracycline analogues, and approximately 2000 derivatives have been developed during the past 20 years.[1] Many modifi- cations have been performed in the deoxysugar unit of anthra- cyclines because this portion of the molecule appeared to be positioned in the minor groove adjacent to the intercalation site, and it plays a role in forming and stabilizing interactions in the ternary complex DNA–topoisomerase II–drug complex through specific direct molecular contact. Chemical and config- urational changes in the sugar moiety of the anthracycline molecules were reported to attenuate their cytotoxic activity.[6] However, the chemical synthesis and modifications of the anthracycline compounds, especially their deoxysugar-contain- ing parts is not a trivial operation.[7] Combinatorial biosynthesis is an alternative technology for accessing otherwise unavaila- ble structures through the combinatorial application of genetic ChemBioChem 2007, 8, 599 – 602 [a] Dr. A. New aranciamycins obtained after expression of the 41-2C-06 cosmid in S. fradiae A0 and S. diastatochromogenes TE6028. aglycone aranciamycinone and the sugar 2-O-methyl-l-rham- nose.[9] Aranciamycin derivatives were found to inhibit the DNA synthesis of Yoshida sacroma tumor cells.[10] Interestingly, in contrast to other anthracyclines, aranciamycins are specific collagenase inhibitors, which is interesting for the treatment of nonmalignant diseases. In this paper, we report the cloning and sequencing of the aranciamycin biosynthetic gene cluster (ara-cluster) from S. echinatus. A S. echinatus genomic cosmid library was generated as Gdescribed[11] by using the Streptomyces--E. coli shuttle vector pOJ436.[12] The actI PKS gene was used to probe the cosmid Glibrary as described in ref. [13]. One cosmid (cosmid 412C06), that was hybridized to the probe was sequenced. 24 open reading frames (ORFs) were detected on a 35.9 kb region.

The annotation analysis revealed candidate genes that puta- tively encode biosynthetic-, regulatory- and resistance-confer- ring functions (Table 1). ORFs 11, 10, 9, which are found in a typical type II PKS arrangement most probably encode a keto- synthase (KS)a, a KSb, and an acyl carrier protein (ACP).[14] These ORFs are flanked by genes that encode an aromatase (ORF7), a ketoreductase (ORF8), and two cyclases (ORF6 and ORF12). ORFs 13, 14, and 15 might encode a response regula- tor, a signal-transduction histidine kinase and a pathway-spe- cific transcription activator, respectively.[15] An additional regu- latory gene is ORF4, which is situated at the 5’-end of the clus- ter. ORF16 might encode an anthrone-type oxygenase that in- troduces oxygen to the C-12 position of aranciamycinone. ORF22 and ORF5, encode a FAD-dependent and a cytochrome P450-dependent oxygenase, respectively, and are expected to be responsible for introducing oxygens into positions C-8 and C-10 of the aranciamycin molecule. Two methyltransferases (MTs), which are encoded by ORF24 and ORF20 are assumed to catalyze the methyl transfer to the C’-2 position of l-rham- nose and to the C-8-OH position of the aglycon, respectively. ORF21 encodes a glycosyltransferase (AraGT), which attaches

l-rhamnose to the C-7 position of aranciamycinone.[16] Interest- ingly, AraGT is sufficiently reactive to glycosylate the anthracy- cline backbone of aranciamycinone. It has been described that it does not need a partner protein for activation.[16] This is in contrast to AknT and StfG, which are both involved in the bio- synthesis of anthracycline derivatives.[17] Genes involved in dTDP-l-rhamnose biosynthesis have not been discovered, even after sequencing overlapping cosmids. Interestingly, the gene clusters responsible for the biosynthesis of the l-rhamnose- containing antibiotics steffimycin, elloramycin, and spinosynin also do not contain dTDP-l-rhamnose biosynthetic genes.[18–20] To prove that the isolated cluster is involved in the biosyn- thesis of aranciamycin, cosmid 41-2C-06 was expressed in S. albus. An analysis of the products that were accumulated by S. albus 41-2C-06 showed the production of the aranciamycin aglycon (Scheme 1). No glycosylated compounds were detecta- ble by HPLC-MS. The most likely explanation for this observa- tion is that S. albus can not provide dTDP-l-rhamnose to com- plete the biosynthesis of aranciamycin.

To investigate the sugar substrate specificity of AraGT, cosmid 41-2C-06 was expressed in Streptomyces fradiae A0 and in Streptomyces diastatochromogenes TE6028. Both strains are capable of generating nucleotide-activated deoxysugars. dTDP–d-amicetose and dTDP–l-anexose are necessary precur- sors for the biosynthesis of polyketomycin in S. diastatochro- mogenes and dTDP–l-rhodinose and dTDP–d-olivose are needed for the biosynthesis of urdamycin A in S. fradiae. S. dia- statochromogenes TE6028 and S. fradiae A0, which carry cosmid 41-2C-06, produced several novel products. Four com- pounds, named aranciamycinone, aranciamycins A, C, and D were isolated from S. diastatochromogenes TE6028 and two compounds, namely aranciamycinone and aranciamycin B Table 1. were isolated from S. fradiae A0. The structures of all of the compounds were elucidated by NMR spectroscopy and MS. (see the Supporting Information). Aranciamycins A, B, C and D all lack the methoxy group at position C-8, but show differen- ces in their sugar components. Surprisingly, aranciamycin A contains 2-O-methyl-l-rhamnose; this indicates that S. diastato- chromogenes TE6028 also generates dNDP–l-rhamnose. That aranciamycin B contains l-rhodinose, aranciamycin C contains l-axenose d-amicetose (Scheme 1) indicates that AraGT has a broad flexibility for dif- ferent sugars. To verify if AraGT was indeed responsible for the sugar transfer to the aranciamycin aglycon, we inactivated araGT on cosmid 41-2C-06 by introducing the spectinomycin- resistance cassette into the gene by redET technology. The mu- tated cosmid 41-2C-06::aadA was transferred into S. fradiae A0 and S. diastatochromogenes TE6028. Neither of these strains produced glycosylated aranciamycin derivatives; this indicates that AraGT is responsible for the transfer of all of the sugar res- idues mentioned above. Activities of new aranciamycins against MaTu and MCF7 cells proliferation were determined by using the KV-assay. Arancia- mycins B and D, which contain l-rhodinose and d-amicetose, respectively, showed the best inhibition activities; this indicates the relevance of the sugar moiety for anticancer activity. One key element for the success in the discovery of new car- bohydrate-containing products is the degree of promiscuity of glycosyltransferases toward both the glycosyl donor and ac- ceptor. There are successful examples of promiscuous glycosyl- transferases, like UrdGT2 and ElmGT, which have been used to generate libraries of new hybrid aromatic compounds by com- binatorial biosynthesis.[21] Our glycosyltransferase gene tool box now contains an additional candidate that is useful for the

In summary, we have successfully identified a novel PKS II gene cluster that is responsible for the production of arancia- mycin. The new very flexible glycosyltransferase AraGT accepts different nucleotide-activated d- and l-sugars as substrates. The newly generated aranciamycin derivatives displayed anti- proliferative activity against MaTu and MCF7 cells. Future work will be done to investigate the aglycon flexibility of this AraGT.

Bacterial strains and culture conditions: DNA of the aranciamycin producer Streptomyces echinatus T#303 was used as the source for the construction of a genomic DNA library. S. fradiae A0 and S. dia- statochromogenes TE6028 served as host strains for heterologous expression experiments. For aranciamycin production strains were cultivated as previously described for 5 days at 28 8C.[9] Cosmid 41-2C-06 was introduced to the streptomyces strain via conjuga- Gtion from E. coli ET12567 (pUZ8002). Exconjugants were selected with apramycin (Sigma) at 25 mg mL(cid:1)1 and phosphomycin at 200 mg mL(cid:1)1 in solid medium. E. coli strain XL1-Blue served as hosts for library construction and routine subcloning, respectively. E. coli strains were grown in LB medium that was supplemented with Gampicillin (100 mg mL(cid:1)1) and apramycin (25 mg mL(cid:1)1) for selection. Conjugation experiments between E. coli and streptomycetes have been performed as described in ref. [22, 23]. Plasmids and general DNA procedures: DNA isolation, plasmid preparation, restriction digests, gel electrophoresis and ligation re- actions were conducted according to standard methods.[24] pBlue- script II SK(+) (Stratagene) was the routine vector for the subclon- ing and preparation of DNA templates for sequencing.

DNA sequencing and computer-assisted sequence analysis: Nu- cleotide sequences were determined on an ABI sequencer at 4- Base Lab GmbH (Reutlingen, Germany) and at GATC Biotech AG (Konstanz, Germany) by using standard primers (M13 universal and reverse, T3, and T7) or customized, internal primers. Computer-as- sisted analysis was done with the DNASIS software package (ver- sion 2.1, 1995; Hitachi Software Engineering) and the FramePlot software at http://www.nih.go.jp/_jun/cgi-bin/frameplot.pl.[25] Data- base comparison was performed with the BLAST search tools on the server of the National Center for Biotechnology Information, Bethesda, MD.[26] To analyze polyketide synthase domains, the SEARCHPKS program (at http://www.nii.res.in/searchpks.html) of- fered by the National Institute of Immunology, New Delhi, India, was used.[27] Nucleotide sequence accession number: The sequence reported here has been deposited into the GenBank database under the Gaccession number DQ915964. Isolation and detection of metabolites: The S. fradiae, S. echinatus and S. diastatochromogenes strains were grown in SG medium, start pH 7.2, for 5 days at 30 8C in a rotary shaker at 200 rpm. Aran- Gciamycins were extracted from liquid culture broths of wild-type and recombinant strains with ethyl acetate. The extracts were dried over Na2SO4, concentrated in vacuo, and then the residue was redissolved in methanol. The residue from the concentrated extract of recombinant strains was subjected to repeated silica gel column chromatography in methanol for purification. Aranciamy- cins were identified by comparison of the extracts, by HPLC and by MS. Analytical HPLC-MS runs were performed on a Agilent system ChemBioChem 2007, 8, 599 – 602 F 2007 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim

equipped with a Grom-SL C18 (ODS octadecyl) column (40 R 3 mm). Metabolites were eluted with an ACN/H2O gradient ranging from 60 % to 80 % ACN in 10 min at a flow rate of 1.0 mL min(cid:1)1 and UV detection was performed at 451 nm. The retention times were: demethoxy-aranciamycinone, tR = 3.55 min; aranciamycin A, tR = 3.52 min; aranciamycin B, tR = 3.84 min; aranciamycin D tR = 4.12 min. High-resolution ESI-MS was measured by using a Micromass QTOF2 mass spectrometer. Mass spectra data for the compounds were: demethoxy-aranciamyci- none, m/z 340.0974 (C19H16O6); aranciamycin A, m/z 500.1682 (C26H28O10); aranciamycin B, m/z 454.1628 (C25H26O8); aranciamy- cin C, m/z 484.1733 (C26H28O9); aranciamycin D, m/z 454.1628 (C25H26O8) all [M] +. NMR spectroscopy measurements were carried out on a Bruker AMX 600 spectrometer.

Testing of anticancer activity of aranciamycins: The MCF-7 was obtained from Dr. Marc Lippman, (University of Michigan) and the MATU cells from I. Fichtner (MDC, Berlin, Germany). All human cancer cell lines were stored in frozen stocks (20 % FCS plus 10 % DMSO) and are used up for 10 passages only. Cells were routinely maintained in phenol red free RPMI medium (Seromed) supple- mented with 200 mU mL(cid:1)1 insulin (Sigma) and 10 % of fetal calf serum (FCS) (Gibco BRL). Cells are cultivated in a humified incuba- tor at 5 % CO2. Cell culture medium was changed twice per week and cells were passaged weekly by detaching the cells with T/E (0.05 % trypsin plus 0.02 % EDTA in PBS) (Seromed, Berlin, Germany) and replating 1 R 106 cells per 10 mL in a T75 cm2 cell culture flask (Costar, Corning, NY). Human cancer cells were plated in a 96-well microtiter plate. After 24 h, the cells were exposed continuously to the test compounds for 4 days. On day 4, the cell proliferation was determined by staining with crystal violet. The absorbance was es- timated photometrically at 595 nm, and the percentage change of cell growth was calculated in relation to the control group. Sub- confluent cells were detached with trypsin/EDTA and 5000 cells per well were plated in 200 mL of medium plus 10 % serum in a 96-well plate (Costar). After 24 h the cells were exposed continuously for 3 days to the investigational compounds. The cell number was de- termined by staining with crystal violet. The cell monolayers were fixed for 15 min at room temperature by the addition of glutar- Galdehyde at a final concentration of 1 % (Merck), washed 3 times with water, incubated for 20 min with 200 mL of crystal violet (Sigma–Aldrich; 0.1 % in water, pH 3.5), washed 3 times with water, and after the addition of 100

1 % (Merck), washed 3 times with water, incubated for 20 min with 200 mL of crystal violet (Sigma–Aldrich; 0.1 % in water, pH 3.5), washed 3 times with water, and after the addition of 100 mL of acetic acid (10 % in water) the extinction was measured. The absorbance was determined photo- metrically with a SL microtiter plate reader (SLT Lab Instruments, Crailsheim, Germany) at 595 nm and the percentage change of cell growth was calculated in relation to the control groups.
